ty between sender and recipient. This book situatesletters within medieval theories of composition and habits of reception, to argue that even mundane letters of governance were rhetorical texts. It focuses on the example of Edward I of England, whose rhetorical prowess was noted,often critically, by contemporaries. It shows how the king's correspondence varied in tone, vocabulary and structure across his reign and between recipients, revealing an unexpected dynamism of political discourse. Moving betweenhistorical context and close readings of individual letters, this volume identifies letter-writing as an art through which the king and his government attempted to negotiate and mould relationships with political communities anddiplomatic interlocutors alike. KATHLEEN B. NEAL is Lecturer in History at Monash University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunication in politicszGreat BritainxHistory. 0aEdward-I,-King of England,-1239-1307. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAlexander III of Scotland.  aBritain.  aCrisis of 1297.  aFalcon called Marmaduke.  aFirst Scottish War of Independence.  aJohn I of Scotland.  aars dictaminis.  aaurality.  acounsel.  adictamen.  adiplomacy.  agreat seal.  aidentity.  ajustice.  akinship.  aletter-writing.  aliterate.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311143100040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800101104?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800101104423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800101104/original  a978-3-11-143100-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles